          </sec>
          <sec id="OralCephalosporins.Comment">
            <title>Comment</title>
            <p>The prolonged course of cholestasis with no obvious cause was most likely due to drug induced liver injury, and cefuroxime (a third generation, orally available cephalosporin) was the most likely cause. The long incubation period is unusual for cephalosporin related liver injury. Furthermore, rechallenge with cephalexin and then with cefuroxime appeared to worsen the course minimally, if at all, but may have been the reason for the delayed recovery. A year after the initial presentation, the patient was without symptoms, but serum enzymes were still mildly abnormal. Ultimately, however, even these mild biochemical abnormalities resolved.</p>
          </sec>
